My family, my marriage is at stake.

01:51:38.286 --> 01:51:40.926
We just have to
check out everything in a murder case.

01:51:41.006 --> 01:51:43.406
OK, but I'm not your man.

01:51:43.886 --> 01:51:47.126
I know it's not the most
honorable thing to cheat on your wife,

01:51:47.206 --> 01:51:49.446
but that does not make me a murderer.

01:51:49.606 --> 01:51:52.526
We're... obligated
to review the situation.

01:51:52.606 --> 01:51:54.606
I understand
it's sensitive stuff for you.

01:51:54.686 --> 01:51:56.286
And if we have to talk to you again,

01:51:56.366 --> 01:51:58.686
we'll do everything in our power
to keep it very private.

01:51:58.766 --> 01:52:00.286
Your personal life's your own.

01:52:00.366 --> 01:52:04.206
We're not making any moral judgments,
just investigating a crime.

01:52:14.406 --> 01:52:16.486
I understand.

01:52:17.406 --> 01:52:19.046
Look...

01:52:19.126 --> 01:52:21.326
...if you have to get
in contact with me again,

01:52:21.406 --> 01:52:23.406
which, God in heaven,
I hope you don't,

01:52:23.486 --> 01:52:25.446
please call me on my mobile.

01:52:25.886 --> 01:52:27.926
This is my number.

01:52:29.806 --> 01:52:31.406
Thanks.

01:52:32.126 --> 01:52:33.086
One other thing.

01:52:33.166 --> 01:52:35.566
Do you own or have access to a shotgun?

01:52:37.766 --> 01:52:39.206
Me?

01:52:39.406 --> 01:52:40.606
No.

01:52:40.686 --> 01:52:44.566
My father-in-law shoots
on the estate, but not me.

01:52:44.646 --> 01:52:46.806
You can check it out, but...

01:52:47.806 --> 01:52:51.766
...I beg you to consider mine
and his position.

01:52:51.846 --> 01:52:53.926
Of course.

01:52:56.926 --> 01:52:58.886
Thank you.

01:53:07.526 --> 01:53:09.526
So, what do you think?

01:53:10.046 --> 01:53:11.846
I think it's what it looks like.

01:53:11.926 --> 01:53:13.966
Someone robbed and killed Mrs. Eastby,

01:53:14.046 --> 01:53:17.606
who was surprised leaving,
and killed Nola Rice.

01:53:18.646 --> 01:53:22.206
Yeah, I know. I know, it's got
drug robbery written all over it.

01:53:22.286 --> 01:53:24.286
He's 'specting a baby.

01:53:24.486 --> 01:53:26.886
OK, he's not gonna win
a medal for fidelity, but...

01:53:28.046 --> 01:53:29.646
...we can find out discreetly enough

01:53:29.726 --> 01:53:32.726
whether the Hewetts
had a shotgun unaccounted for.

01:53:34.606 --> 01:53:38.686
I don't think that he would know the
first thing about stealing one though,

01:53:38.766 --> 01:53:41.566
never mind sawing one off.

01:53:42.406 --> 01:53:45.366
It's a bit of a stretch.
He's got no previous convictions.

01:53:45.446 --> 01:53:47.166
Not even a speeding ticket.

01:53:47.246 --> 01:53:50.046
The coroner says
that Eastby was killed first.

01:53:50.126 --> 01:53:52.446
- Yeah.
- There's no sign of a forced entry.

01:53:52.526 --> 01:53:54.766
So Mrs. Eastby knew the killer,
if she let him in.

01:53:54.846 --> 01:53:56.326
Well, come on, Mike.

01:53:56.406 --> 01:53:58.246
Ninety percent
of the crimes we go out on,

01:53:58.286 --> 01:54:00.446
people open their doors
and invite the criminals in.

01:54:00.526 --> 01:54:02.846
Yeah, I know, you're right.
I'm just thinking out loud.

01:54:02.926 --> 01:54:05.886
- It's just he's got a real motive.
- Yeah, maybe.

01:54:05.966 --> 01:54:10.566
But a motive, as you and I
both painfully know, is not a case.

01:54:10.646 --> 01:54:13.686
I'm torn because the Rice murder
was clearly an afterthought,

01:54:13.766 --> 01:54:15.606
but I'd love to pursue it a little more.

01:54:15.686 --> 01:54:19.046
But I'm reluctant to fish around
and cause problems for everybody.

01:54:19.126 --> 01:54:21.406
Well, if something develops,
we can pursue it.

01:54:21.486 --> 01:54:24.206
I doubt anything's
gonna drop into our laps.

01:56:21.966 --> 01:56:23.646
Chris.

01:56:33.606 --> 01:56:35.366
Nola...

01:56:37.446 --> 01:56:39.686
...it wasn't easy.

01:56:40.646 --> 01:56:43.446
But when the time came,
I could pull the trigger.

01:56:45.326 --> 01:56:48.326
You never know who your neighbors are
till there's a crisis.

01:56:49.926 --> 01:56:54.126
You can learn to push the guilt
under the rug and... go on.

01:56:55.326 --> 01:56:57.086
You have to.

01:56:57.166 --> 01:56:59.686
Otherwise it overwhelms you.

01:56:59.766 --> 01:57:01.926
And what about me?

01:57:01.966 --> 01:57:04.726
What about the next-door neighbor?

01:57:05.486 --> 01:57:08.486
I had no involvement
in this awful affair.

01:57:09.926 --> 01:57:14.846
Is there no problem about me
having to die as an innocent bystander?

01:57:16.766 --> 01:57:21.166
The innocent are sometimes slain
to make way for a grander scheme.

01:57:23.246 --> 01:57:25.486
You were collateral damage.

01:57:25.566 --> 01:57:28.046
So was your own child.

01:57:32.286 --> 01:57:34.286
Sophocles said:

01:57:35.766 --> 01:57:37.966
"To never have been born

01:57:38.566 --> 01:57:41.046
may be the greatest boon of all."

01:57:43.406 --> 01:57:45.726
Prepare to pay the price, Chris.

01:57:46.646 --> 01:57:48.806
Your actions were clumsy.

01:57:48.886 --> 01:57:50.566
Full of holes.

01:57:50.646 --> 01:57:53.846
Almost like someone
begging to be found out.

01:57:57.326 --> 01:58:00.326
It would be fitting
if I were apprehended

01:58:00.366 --> 01:58:02.286
and punished.

01:58:03.406 --> 01:58:07.126
At least there would be
some small sign of justice.

01:58:07.206 --> 01:58:10.206
Some small...

01:58:10.886 --> 01:58:14.326
...measure of hope
for the possibility of meaning.

01:58:16.726 --> 01:58:19.886
Chris Wilton killed them.
I see how he did it.

01:58:19.966 --> 01:58:21.726
What?

01:58:22.926 --> 01:58:24.486
It's as we speculated

01:58:24.566 --> 01:58:26.966
and said was too elaborate,
but that's what he did.

01:58:27.046 --> 01:58:30.126
He killed the next-door neighbor first
to throw us off the scent

01:58:30.206 --> 01:58:31.886
and set up the appearance of a robbery.

01:58:31.966 --> 01:58:32.966
He waited in the hall.

01:58:33.046 --> 01:58:34.926
He knew she'd be back
the same time as usual,

01:58:35.006 --> 01:58:38.286
and he killed her, making it seem like
she surprised a burglar running out.

01:58:38.366 --> 01:58:40.486
He planned it all so he could
make the theater in time

01:58:40.566 --> 01:58:42.806
to strengthen his alibi,
if one became necessary.

01:58:42.886 --> 01:58:45.406
Now, I haven't figured out
the weapon problem,

01:58:45.486 --> 01:58:46.966
and I know it's a lot to ask a jury,

01:58:47.006 --> 01:58:49.206
but the correctness of it
came to me in my sleep

01:58:49.286 --> 01:58:51.046
and I am going to break this case.

01:58:51.126 --> 01:58:52.966
I hate to be the bearer
of bad news, Mike.

01:58:53.046 --> 01:58:54.006
What?

01:58:54.086 --> 01:58:56.046
Not that your dream
isn't of primary interest to a jury.

01:58:56.086 --> 01:58:57.366
What's the bad news?

01:58:57.446 --> 01:59:00.326
There was another shooting
in the area last night, 4am.

01:59:00.406 --> 01:59:03.126
A drug addict killed.
Looks like a drug sale turned nasty.

01:59:03.206 --> 01:59:06.446
What, and he confessed
to killing two women before he died?

01:59:06.526 --> 01:59:08.206
No, he didn't have to.

01:59:08.286 --> 01:59:11.486
The old woman's wedding ring
was right in his pocket.

01:59:12.166 --> 01:59:15.406
- No.
- Name and date engraved right on it.

01:59:16.406 --> 01:59:19.606
- I don't believe it.
- I know. I know.

01:59:19.686 --> 01:59:22.006
Your case looked good, lots of motive.

01:59:22.046 --> 01:59:24.326
But his motive
was pretty strong too. Heroin.

01:59:24.646 --> 01:59:27.046
Junkie with a long string
of convictions.

01:59:27.646 --> 01:59:29.646
Killed by one of his own, no doubt.

01:59:29.726 --> 01:59:31.566
Come on, I'll buy you breakfast.

01:59:31.646 --> 01:59:33.966
You can traumatize me
with the rest of your dreams.

01:59:34.046 --> 01:59:35.446
No, wait.

01:59:35.486 --> 01:59:39.486
What if Wilton did it, threw the
jewels away, this guy finds them?

01:59:40.926 --> 01:59:44.286
I don't know.
See what tonight's dream tells you.

01:59:44.366 --> 01:59:47.086
I'm sure a jury will be interested.

01:59:47.166 --> 01:59:49.006
Come on.

01:59:50.366 --> 01:59:51.606
I give up.

01:59:51.686 --> 01:59:53.486
I knew Wilton didn't do it.

01:59:53.566 --> 01:59:55.886
He's another poor schmuck
who cheated on his wife.

01:59:55.966 --> 01:59:59.286
When you see those pictures
of Nola Rice, you can see why though.

02:00:00.006 --> 02:00:02.766
What a world. Am I right?

02:00:03.246 --> 02:00:06.206
Careful, careful.
I'm always afraid they'll drop.

02:00:06.286 --> 02:00:09.286
- Oh, chill out, Dad.
- Babies are so, so soft.

02:00:09.366 --> 02:00:11.326
Right. Champagne.

02:00:11.366 --> 02:00:13.606
- I think he's got your eyes, Chloe.
- Really?

02:00:13.686 --> 02:00:16.046
I think he's got
your coloring darling, I really do.

02:00:16.126 --> 02:00:19.366
Mummy, you can't tell anything yet.
They change all the time.

02:00:20.726 --> 02:00:22.286
- My nephew.
- Uncle, Uncle Tom.

02:00:22.366 --> 02:00:25.006
- Oh, look at these flowers.
- No, he does look like Christopher.

02:00:25.086 --> 02:00:28.566
Actually, speaking of which, didn't you
move into Alan Sinclair's old office?

02:00:28.646 --> 02:00:31.006
- You lucky swine.
- Oh, Mummy, look, he's dreaming.

02:00:31.086 --> 02:00:32.566
Let's work on number two. Come on.

02:00:32.646 --> 02:00:36.006
Come on, he is a handsome boy.
Look at that face.

02:00:36.086 --> 02:00:37.326
Yeah, he's gorgeous.

02:00:37.406 --> 02:00:39.446
Right, here we are. Eleanor. Please...

02:00:39.526 --> 02:00:40.886
- Chloe...
- Good stuff, Papa.

02:00:40.926 --> 02:00:42.446
- Thank you, darling. There you are.
- There we go.

02:00:42.526 --> 02:00:44.686
- It's all right, you stay there.
- I'll pass them round, shall I?

02:00:44.726 --> 02:00:45.726
Please do.

02:00:45.806 --> 02:00:46.886
- What a good idea.
- Darling, have one.

02:00:46.926 --> 02:00:49.166
- To Terence Elliot Wilton.
- Yes.

02:00:49.246 --> 02:00:51.646
With parents like Chloe and Chris,

02:00:51.726 --> 02:00:54.526
this child will be great
at anything he sets his mind to.

02:00:54.566 --> 02:00:56.126
- Thank you, Mummy.
- He will. He...

02:00:56.206 --> 02:00:58.126
Do you know what,
I don't care if he's great.

02:00:58.206 --> 02:00:59.526
I just hope that he's lucky.

02:00:59.606 --> 02:01:01.206
- Oh, lovely.
- What a lovely thought.

02:01:01.286 --> 02:01:02.606
- He probably will be.
- Absolutely adorable.

02:01:02.686 --> 02:01:04.526
- Mummy, are you sure I'm allowed this?
- Yes, yes.

02:01:04.606 --> 02:01:07.446
- Yes, of course you are.
- You haven't had any for months.

02:01:07.486 --> 02:01:08.886
I'd get it down you now, while you can.

02:01:08.966 --> 02:01:10.246
Isn't he handsome?
My God, he's handsome.

02:01:10.326 --> 02:01:12.486
Bet you any money
the next one's a girl.

02:01:14.646 --> 02:01:16.046
What are you saying about him?

02:01:16.126 --> 02:01:18.126
I was just saying he's got
the most adorable cheeks.

02:01:18.206 --> 02:01:22.166
We were just saying how handsome he is.
Just so extraordinarily handsome.

02:01:22.246 --> 02:01:23.526
I wonder what he's thinking.

02:01:23.566 --> 02:01:24.846
Well, you know, they said
he was a thinker. The nurses.

02:01:24.926 --> 02:01:26.566
- Deep thoughts. Deep thoughts.
- Here we are.

02:01:26.646 --> 02:01:28.566
- To Terence.
- To Terence.

02:01:28.646 --> 02:01:31.326
- To Terence.
- And all that sail on him.

